  "definitions": [
    "(transitive) to be unwilling to accept or receive; to refuse, decline, reject\n",
    "(transitive) to be unwilling to give or concede; to deny\nCi sono favori che ad un amico non si possono rifiutare. ― There are favors you just can't deny a friend. (literally, “There are favors that, to a friend, one can't deny.”)",
    "(transitive, followed by di) to be unwilling to do (something); to refuse\nMia sorella rifiuta di parlarmi. ― My sister refuses to talk to me.",
    "(archaic, rare, transitive) to give up (something), to refuse",
    "(archaic, rare, transitive) to disown\nIl Leopardi rifiutò molte sue poesie giovanili. ― Leopardi disowned many of the poems of his youth."
  ],
  "description": "rifiutare",
  "etymology": "From Latin refūtāre, present active infinitive form of refūtō (“I oppose”, “I refute”). The -i- was an influence by fiutare (“to sniff”). Doublet of refutare.",
